WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:02.320
And welcome to

00:00:03.800 --> 00:00:07.280
It's not just code managing an open source project

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:13.600
I'd like to introduce the open source program director from Posit, Tracy Teal

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:23.680
Thank you, I'm super excited to be here today

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:26.320
speaking on this topic

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:30.040
You may wonder why this topic is in this session

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:35.820
And that's because I had a surprise opportunity to give this talk today because someone canceled

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:42.040
But this is one of my favorite topics, and I love the panel discussion yesterday

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:46.639
So I'm excited to get to spend a little bit more time on this topic

00:00:47.799 --> 00:00:49.439
and so

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:52.540
I'm preaching to the choir in this conference

00:00:53.060 --> 00:00:58.340
To say that open source software is the roads and bridges of technology

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:02.660
So when I say that, you know, what do we mean?

00:01:03.139 --> 00:01:08.180
You open up your phone, your social media, your news, your medical records, your bank

00:01:08.459 --> 00:01:13.860
They are all using free and public code. And this is a theme that we've been hearing throughout this meeting

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:21.900
Especially in the panel yesterday, and this is something that Nadia Ekbal highlighted in a report that she did

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:24.540
When she was a VC

00:01:25.059 --> 00:01:33.220
She was looking for the biggest sort of unfunded opportunities in the tech space and what she encountered was open source

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:37.779
And so she worked on this report

00:01:38.779 --> 00:01:40.980
to generate ideas about

00:01:41.660 --> 00:01:45.620
Why this was happening and what the structure of open source looked like

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.459
But what we see in open source is this sort of

00:01:51.459 --> 00:01:56.419
Inverse pyramid structure, right, where we have a lot of people who are using it, users

00:01:57.099 --> 00:02:01.779
Who use an open source solution as is without adapting or modifying it

00:02:01.779 --> 00:02:06.860
This is the biggest group of folks out there using open source software

00:02:07.699 --> 00:02:14.059
There's integrators, people who integrate one or more open source components to create an application

00:02:14.699 --> 00:02:20.220
So they may be doing a little bit modification, a little more what's going on under the hood in some of these projects

00:02:21.419 --> 00:02:26.979
Then you have contributors, people who provide changes and improvements to the open source software

00:02:27.619 --> 00:02:30.179
Ecosystem and then finally you have

00:02:30.979 --> 00:02:36.899
Maintainers and these are the people who develop and control the main source code and manage the project

00:02:37.419 --> 00:02:42.100
So we see that this is not necessarily like a very stable structure

00:02:43.139 --> 00:02:46.779
The way that it's designed and I think that a lot of us in this room

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:52.460
Have experienced this, this feeling of sort of being somewhere in this pyramid

00:02:52.979 --> 00:03:01.059
Where there is a weight on top of you in terms of the responsibilities that you have to your team and your communities

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:06.740
And so a lot of times too, these are volunteers, right?

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:09.740
So these are not necessarily even positions that are paid

00:03:10.259 --> 00:03:12.380
The people that are supporting these structures

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:17.460
So, why is this a topic that is so interesting, exciting and important to me?

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:21.460
Well, I started in open source software development in bioinformatics

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:26.259
And I wrote some software that mainly I used

00:03:26.259 --> 00:03:28.740
But, you know, my team used it too

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:32.139
And I started to write projects that that got more use

00:03:32.139 --> 00:03:36.139
And I started to encounter like some of the edge cases of some of these things

00:03:36.139 --> 00:03:40.179
But I also realized that especially in bioinformatics

00:03:40.179 --> 00:03:44.699
One thing that was really limiting the advancement of being able to use genomic data

00:03:44.699 --> 00:03:50.699
Was people with the ability to use data science to answer the questions that were important to them

00:03:50.699 --> 00:03:54.699
So I was a part of founding an organization called The Carpentries

00:03:54.699 --> 00:04:01.699
Which is a non-profit organization teaching researchers how to do data science and software development

00:04:01.699 --> 00:04:05.899
And for me that really marked this transition actually in this pyramid

00:04:05.899 --> 00:04:09.899
Where I thought about, oh, I'm developing open source software, I'm a part of this pyramid

00:04:09.899 --> 00:04:13.899
But when I transitioned to running an organization

00:04:13.899 --> 00:04:18.899
I really realized what that meant around maintaining free resources

00:04:18.899 --> 00:04:23.899
And everything that went into it and that I had zero training in any of it

00:04:23.899 --> 00:04:30.899
Alas, my software development skills were not particularly useful in conflict resolution

00:04:31.899 --> 00:04:35.899
In gaining money, running effective meetings

00:04:35.899 --> 00:04:40.899
So these are all things I say I tried to get my MBA via Google

00:04:40.899 --> 00:04:42.899
Every time I was like, I don't know how to do that

00:04:42.899 --> 00:04:44.899
But I bet somebody knows how to do that

00:04:44.899 --> 00:04:46.899
So I would Google it

00:04:46.899 --> 00:04:50.899
So that was like kind of this beginning of this journey for me

00:04:50.899 --> 00:04:52.899
And then I was on the board of NumFocus

00:04:52.899 --> 00:04:55.899
Super excited to be back here at this event

00:04:55.899 --> 00:04:57.899
And I saw that the software development team

00:04:57.899 --> 00:04:59.899
Super excited to be back here at this event

00:04:59.899 --> 00:05:02.899
And I saw that this wasn't just like a me problem

00:05:02.899 --> 00:05:04.899
I wasn't the only one struggling with this

00:05:04.899 --> 00:05:08.899
All of the projects kind of under that NumFocus umbrella

00:05:08.899 --> 00:05:11.899
Were really struggling with a lot of those same challenges

00:05:11.899 --> 00:05:15.899
So now I am at Posit

00:05:15.899 --> 00:05:18.899
I am the open source program director

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:23.899
And so I have the opportunity to work with open source developers every day

00:05:23.899 --> 00:05:27.899
And talk about how kind of Posit fits into this ecosystem of open source

00:05:27.899 --> 00:05:30.899
And I am the chair of the board for PyOpenSci

00:05:30.899 --> 00:05:33.899
And I am the chair of the board for PyOpenSci

00:05:33.899 --> 00:05:37.899
So as I said, this journey where I didn't know what I was doing

00:05:37.899 --> 00:05:39.899
Is not my journey alone

00:05:39.899 --> 00:05:41.899
There are certainly people who do know what they are doing

00:05:41.899 --> 00:05:43.899
As they get into this

00:05:43.899 --> 00:05:47.899
But in general, open source developers have been trying to build roads

00:05:47.899 --> 00:05:52.899
And then we are suddenly asking them to maintain and manage the road crews for a city

00:05:52.899 --> 00:05:54.899
So where do they get those skills?

00:05:54.899 --> 00:05:56.899
Is this even something that people are interested in?

00:05:56.899 --> 00:05:59.899
How do we start to think about this?

00:05:59.899 --> 00:06:03.899
So why do we want to talk about it at a meeting like this?

00:06:03.899 --> 00:06:09.899
And that's because shared challenges are also shared opportunities

00:06:09.899 --> 00:06:11.899
Which opportunities?

00:06:11.899 --> 00:06:16.899
So we are all here together

00:06:16.899 --> 00:06:18.899
We have a lot of shared challenges

00:06:18.899 --> 00:06:21.899
But this also means we don't need to be alone

00:06:21.899 --> 00:06:26.899
These are shared opportunities for us to navigate these waters together

00:06:26.899 --> 00:06:29.899
And talk about what some of the solutions are

00:06:29.899 --> 00:06:32.899
So one thing in particular

00:06:32.899 --> 00:06:38.899
We can provide support, training, and resources for open source maintainers together

00:06:38.899 --> 00:06:41.899
We don't each need to be doing this on our own

00:06:41.899 --> 00:06:44.899
So what does this look like?

00:06:44.899 --> 00:06:48.899
So I'm going to talk about five different areas

00:06:48.899 --> 00:06:52.899
That we can think about in maintaining open source projects

00:06:52.899 --> 00:06:55.899
And none of this here is a should

00:06:55.899 --> 00:06:57.899
These are all questions

00:06:57.899 --> 00:07:00.899
These are things that you can consider

00:07:00.899 --> 00:07:02.899
Every project is going to be different

00:07:02.899 --> 00:07:06.899
If I'm going to say should for me, it's not should for you

00:07:06.899 --> 00:07:11.899
So in general, what I'm posing are more questions than answers in this

00:07:11.899 --> 00:07:15.899
But one of the challenges when you're working in an open source project

00:07:15.899 --> 00:07:18.899
Is that you get going on the project

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:20.899
And that's sort of where all your energy is

00:07:20.899 --> 00:07:23.899
And so you don't have that space to step back and think about

00:07:23.899 --> 00:07:26.899
Why am I doing this? What's important?

00:07:26.899 --> 00:07:29.899
So just a sense in this room

00:07:29.899 --> 00:07:32.899
How many people have contributed to an open source project?

00:07:32.899 --> 00:07:38.899
And how many people feel like they're in some kind of management or maintenance group?

00:07:38.899 --> 00:07:44.899
And how many of you have had training in business or conflict resolution?

00:07:45.899 --> 00:07:48.899
Yeah, okay, great, perfect

00:07:48.899 --> 00:07:52.899
If you all have, well then you were going to tell me more, please

00:07:52.899 --> 00:07:54.899
I'm always learning

00:07:54.899 --> 00:07:59.899
So these are things that I only realized far into a project

00:07:59.899 --> 00:08:01.899
That I needed to consider

00:08:01.899 --> 00:08:05.899
And then, again, especially working across all these different open source projects

00:08:05.899 --> 00:08:10.899
Realized that those were things that we wanted to be thinking about from the start

00:08:10.899 --> 00:08:15.899
So the very first thing, this maybe seems a little bit strange

00:08:15.899 --> 00:08:18.899
But it's identifying your project goals

00:08:18.899 --> 00:08:21.899
Because a lot of times when you start a project

00:08:21.899 --> 00:08:25.899
You are trying to solve a problem that you have

00:08:25.899 --> 00:08:28.899
And maybe you write it just for yourself or for your team

00:08:28.899 --> 00:08:30.899
And then some people pick it up and they start using it

00:08:30.899 --> 00:08:33.900
And you're like, wow, that's cool, that's amazing

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:35.900
And sort of before you know it

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:39.900
Other people have sort of like decided what this project is about without you

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:41.900
And that's not bad

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:45.900
But you actually do get to decide what the goals of this project are

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:50.900
Just because you start something doesn't mean that you need to maintain it forever

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:53.900
Doesn't mean that you need to implement every feature

00:08:53.900 --> 00:08:57.900
So it's worth taking the time to consider your goals

00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:00.900
So the first thing you have to do is take a breath

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:04.900
Because, again, this project may have gotten away from you a little bit

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:07.900
So who is this for?

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:09.900
Who are you creating this project for?

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:14.900
What's the kind of person that you're thinking about this tool is for?

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:17.900
How reliable is this going to be?

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:20.900
Is this something that people are going to be using in production?

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:22.900
Big environments?

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:25.900
Or is this something that someone's using in a lab

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:27.900
And you can kind of print out a bunch of error messages

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:29.900
Or share it with some caveats?

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:33.900
What's the importance of reliability for this software?

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:36.900
What kinds of input will be important?

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:41.900
Not like data input, but what kind of feedback?

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:43.900
What do you want to hear about?

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:47.900
What do you need to learn as people use this?

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:51.900
And then finally, and this is actually really hard

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:56.900
But what's your vision of what will be possible if this software exists?

00:09:56.900 --> 00:10:01.900
The world and the future will be like X if this software exists

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:04.900
And that seems like, oh, maybe that's a grand statement

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:06.900
But you're doing it for those reasons

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:09.900
What is your vision for this software?

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:11.900
So these are really hard questions

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.900
Everything I'm posing here, none of it is a jest

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:18.900
It is all something that you have to spend time with and it takes time

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:21.900
But it's something that is worth taking a day

00:10:21.900 --> 00:10:24.900
Or go take a walk in a park and take your notebook

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:27.900
It's hard to answer these questions for yourself or with your team

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:29.900
When you're in front of your computer

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:35.900
All right, the next one is managing expectations

00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:39.900
You actually get to set your own boundaries

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:47.900
The challenge in this is you have to create those boundaries

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:50.900
Those expectations, and you have to communicate them

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:55.900
So because it's about managing the expectations of the people

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:58.900
Who are using and contributing to this project

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.900
So again, we have five things to consider here

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:04.900
There are certainly more

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:08.900
Stage of the project, like where is it in its development?

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:13.900
How do you want people to treat each other in the space of your project?

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:15.900
And how do you want them to treat you?

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:19.900
How do you want to handle PR submissions and reviews?

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:25.900
Templates, this is something that I'm excited about

00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:30.900
Ways that exist already to help you manage your expectations

00:11:30.900 --> 00:11:34.900
And then licensing, something that came up in the panel yesterday

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:39.900
So stage of the project, I really love this concept in this diagram

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:47.900
This is from the lifecycle package that Posit is one of the developers in here for

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:50.900
And so there are other things that you can consider

00:11:50.900 --> 00:11:52.900
But this is actually really important, this idea

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:54.900
Is this an experimental package?

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:56.900
Are you going to be contributing to it a lot?

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:58.900
Are things going to be changing really quickly?

00:11:58.900 --> 00:11:59.900
Is it stable?

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:03.900
Is it something that people can use and they expect there not to be many changes?

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:06.900
So you can rely on it to behave in a certain way

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:10.900
And then, importantly, superseded and deprecated

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:14.900
Again, if you create something that doesn't need to last forever

00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:18.900
One example is I wrote some software in graduate school

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:20.900
That worked with 454 genomic data

00:12:20.900 --> 00:12:22.900
That package does not need to exist anymore

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:27.900
Because people don't even generate 454 data anymore from genomic sequencers

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:29.900
That's a pretty easy one

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:35.900
But there's other reasons why a package might not really need to be actively maintained anymore

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:39.900
So that's for you to think about

00:12:39.900 --> 00:12:44.900
I think that stage between experimental and stable is unclear

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:46.900
Like nothing is a fine line

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.900
And you kind of might find yourself in a different mode without realizing it

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:51.900
But this is something to keep in mind and come back to

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:55.900
How people treat each other

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.900
I think this is something that's been really positive in the Python community

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:01.900
Over the last several years

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:04.900
Is the expectations of how people behave

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:07.900
In code repositories and at conference

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:10.900
And a lot of this has been around

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:13.900
Really, again, setting those expectations

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:15.900
Not just saying, hey, we should be nice

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:17.900
But let's write it down

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:19.900
What do we mean when we say that?

00:13:19.900 --> 00:13:21.900
What are the consequences for that?

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:26.900
How is it that you share that something isn't going well

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:29.900
And being explicit about that being important?

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:32.900
This is a place where templates are great

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:35.900
GitHub actually has code of conduct templates

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:37.900
So when you start a GitHub repository

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:40.900
You can select this and add a code of conduct to your repository

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:45.900
I will say just putting a code of conduct in your repository is not enough

00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:48.900
You have to think about how you might handle something that comes up

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:53.900
But this is a really important way of writing down

00:13:53.900 --> 00:13:58.900
What you mean when you say how you want people to treat each other

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:00.900
And this is important for you

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:03.900
How do you want people to treat you?

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:09.900
PR submission and review

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:10.900
Contributing guidelines

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:13.900
You see contributing guidelines a lot in GitHub repositories

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:17.900
The timing of this is so awesome

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:19.900
Because I'm so excited about this

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:21.900
PR submission and review

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:26.900
Within Posit, we have an open source reading group

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:29.900
And we're reading a series of blog posts

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:31.900
About good pull requests

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:34.900
Doing good reviews of pull requests

00:14:34.900 --> 00:14:38.900
And from this, Davis Bond put together this tidyverse

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:41.900
Tidy team code review principles

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:44.900
And so you can see there's a lot of categories here

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:46.900
About what does a good PR look like?

00:14:46.900 --> 00:14:49.900
What does a good PR review look like?

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:52.900
So this is setting expectations for the team

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:54.900
We think this is already what we do

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:56.900
But we're trying it out

00:14:56.900 --> 00:15:00.900
But it's also another great way to externalize

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:01.900
How is it?

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:02.900
What's a good PR to us?

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:04.900
What does that look like?

00:15:04.900 --> 00:15:06.900
What are your expectations of our review?

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:08.900
And one thing that I really love

00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:11.900
That Davis and Liam L worked on together

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:14.900
Is these patterns of collaboration

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:17.900
So close-knit collaboration, understudy, external contributors

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:21.900
So the key thing here, again, if you're thinking about managing expectations

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:23.900
The first thing to do is

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:26.900
Which mode of collaboration are we in?

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:28.900
Not every kind of pull request

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:30.900
Or every kind of thing that you're working on

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:33.900
Is going to necessarily have the same relationship

00:15:33.900 --> 00:15:35.900
But if you can agree, this is where we are

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:37.900
Then you have a set of ideas about

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:39.900
What the timing is going to be

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:41.900
When will you get back to me on that PR?

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:44.900
Will you just edit and merge?

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:45.900
Things like that

00:15:45.900 --> 00:15:47.900
And again, it's like

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:50.900
Oh, well, yeah, we kind of all knew this already

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:54.900
But writing it down really helps us stay true

00:15:54.900 --> 00:15:56.900
To what we think we should be doing

00:15:56.900 --> 00:15:58.900
And helps other people understand our process

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:00.900
And maybe something they can use

00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:02.900
If they're building a new project

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:05.900
Okay, templates

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:06.900
This is my favorite

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:08.900
Whenever you're trying to do something new

00:16:08.900 --> 00:16:10.900
It's like somebody's done it before

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:12.900
And there might be a template

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:15.900
So always Google whatever you're trying to do

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:16.900
And template

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:19.900
So there's a lot of great stuff in this space

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:20.900
There's READMEs

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:23.900
This README project around better documentation

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:26.900
We already talked about the code of conduct

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:29.900
READMEs straight from GitHub now

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:32.900
Other kinds of

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:34.900
They're not exactly templates

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:35.900
But are like

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:38.900
What are good package development structures?

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:40.900
So like the Tinyverse has

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:42.900
Use this package

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:43.900
That is like

00:16:43.900 --> 00:16:46.900
You use this to do package development

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:48.900
So it helps you have good practices

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:50.900
In terms of what your package looks like

00:16:50.900 --> 00:16:52.900
And then also your packages look like other people

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:54.900
So people sort of know what to expect

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:57.900
PyOpenSci has been working on these

00:16:57.900 --> 00:17:00.900
Python open source package development guide

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:02.900
So if you're excited about Python packaging

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:04.900
And like who isn't?

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:05.900
I'm serious

00:17:05.900 --> 00:17:06.900
This is amazing

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:08.900
This is Leah Wasser is doing this work

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:10.900
And Juanita is maybe here

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:12.900
She's going to be doing that project

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:13.900
For just a little while

00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:15.900
They have put so much work into

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.900
Like really having community conversations

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:19.900
To say

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:20.900
You know, what works?

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:21.900
What doesn't work?

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:23.900
What's practical?

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:25.900
Really incredible work

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:27.900
That is really important

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:28.900
In these spaces about

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:30.900
Again, what does a Python package look like?

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:31.900
When you're starting

00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:32.900
What does it look like?

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:33.900
What can you expect from the packages

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:35.900
When you take a look at them?

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:38.900
And licensing

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:40.900
I actually don't have too much to say about licensing

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:43.900
I thought it was an interesting conversation yesterday

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:45.900
Yeah, one thing that was interesting was that

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:47.900
Is it really open source?

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:48.900
That conversation

00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:50.900
That was a part of that panel

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:53.900
And open source is defined by

00:17:53.900 --> 00:17:55.900
A set of licenses

00:17:55.900 --> 00:17:57.900
So if it has an open source license

00:17:57.900 --> 00:17:58.900
It is open source

00:17:58.900 --> 00:18:00.900
And when we talk about governance

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:01.900
We can talk about

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:03.900
Maybe some distinctions there

00:18:03.900 --> 00:18:05.900
But yeah, you have to make your choices

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:07.900
On your open source licenses

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:11.900
Alright

00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:13.900
Next one

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:14.900
Easy one

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:18.900
Who is involved in governance conversations

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:20.900
In an open source project right now?

00:18:21.900 --> 00:18:22.900
Okay

00:18:22.900 --> 00:18:24.900
I was like, no one wants it

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:25.900
Okay

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:28.900
So this is hard for sure

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:32.900
This is where having your project goals is important

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:33.900
When I said like

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:34.900
What kinds of input do you need?

00:18:34.900 --> 00:18:35.900
Who is this for?

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:37.900
What do you want to do?

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:38.900
Right?

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:40.900
Like how much time do you have for this project?

00:18:40.900 --> 00:18:41.900
So these are some

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:44.900
The BDFL model is a pretty popular one

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:45.900
Open governance

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:47.900
I think this is where we kind of got

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:48.900
Into this conversation of

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:49.900
Is it really open source?

00:18:49.900 --> 00:18:51.900
Like open source is a license

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:53.900
But there's kind of this open governance idea

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:55.900
There's a community or a committee

00:18:55.900 --> 00:18:56.900
Or something

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:57.900
Something like that

00:18:57.900 --> 00:18:59.900
Like Python is not great

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:00.900
But before

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:02.900
It was BDFL

00:19:03.900 --> 00:19:05.900
Who's going to make your technical decisions

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:07.900
Versus your organizational decisions?

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:10.900
And who's going to do these things?

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:12.900
You might decide on an amazing structure

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:13.900
And then be like, cool

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:14.900
And now who's going to do it?

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:17.900
And everybody looks at their feet

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:20.900
Then it's not really going to be a structure

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:21.900
That's going to work for your team

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:22.900
Or you need to think about

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:24.900
How are you going to recruit someone

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:26.900
Who's excited about those things?

00:19:29.900 --> 00:19:30.900
So yeah

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:31.900
That's definitely a whole topic

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:33.900
I'd love to have a conversation

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:35.900
About governance in particular

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:36.900
So the last one then

00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:38.900
I think is financial support

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:40.900
So this was again

00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:42.900
Something that came up yesterday

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:46.900
And I think this is

00:19:46.900 --> 00:19:47.900
From some of my experience

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:49.900
Having transitioned from a developer

00:19:49.900 --> 00:19:51.900
To leading an organization

00:19:52.900 --> 00:19:54.900
Was the recognition that

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:55.900
This is really

00:19:55.900 --> 00:19:57.900
I mean, in our case it was a non-profit

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:00.900
But a non-profit or a business

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:04.900
Non-focus takes some of that away

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:08.900
By having this project structure

00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:11.900
Where they'll do your back office for you

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:12.900
But you still

00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:13.900
We come back to these

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:14.900
How do you make decisions?

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:15.900
How do you bring in money?

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:16.900
How do you make decisions

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:18.900
About how to spend money?

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:19.900
And this is again

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:20.900
Just a really challenging thing

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:22.900
If you've been a developer

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:24.900
You might not have experience

00:20:24.900 --> 00:20:26.900
In thinking about

00:20:26.900 --> 00:20:27.900
How you generate revenue

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:29.900
How you spend money

00:20:29.900 --> 00:20:33.900
So that might be a little controversial

00:20:33.900 --> 00:20:34.900
Maybe you don't think

00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:36.900
That that's the way it should be

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:38.900
Maybe it's not the way it is for you

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:40.900
Maybe it's not what you've seen

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:41.900
But I think it's something

00:20:41.900 --> 00:20:43.900
To consider and appreciate

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:45.900
So then

00:20:45.900 --> 00:20:47.900
If we do need to think about money

00:20:47.900 --> 00:20:49.900
How much money do we need

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:50.900
To meet the project goals?

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:52.900
Again, what are you trying to do?

00:20:52.900 --> 00:20:53.900
How many people do you need?

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:54.900
What roles do you need?

00:20:54.900 --> 00:20:56.900
How much does it cost to pay those people?

00:20:56.900 --> 00:20:57.900
Or how much does it cost

00:20:57.900 --> 00:20:59.900
For your infrastructure?

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:02.900
Align how you get your money

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:03.900
With your project goals

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:05.900
This is some of the best advice

00:21:05.900 --> 00:21:06.900
That I heard

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:10.900
If your project goals are something

00:21:10.900 --> 00:21:11.900
And you create a way

00:21:11.900 --> 00:21:12.900
To generate money

00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:14.900
That is not aligned with the goals

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:16.900
You're actually running two businesses

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:18.900
You're running the business

00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:20.900
That generates the money

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:23.900
And then you're running the business

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:24.900
That does the other thing

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:26.900
And unless you can find a way

00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:28.900
To wed them together

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:31.900
The money one often wins

00:21:31.900 --> 00:21:33.900
In terms of the time

00:21:33.900 --> 00:21:35.900
Because you have commitments

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:36.900
That you've made

00:21:36.900 --> 00:21:37.900
That you need to honor

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:40.900
And so when we got a grant

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:42.900
From my grant manager

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:43.900
At the Moore Foundation

00:21:43.900 --> 00:21:45.900
Chris Menzel gave us that advice

00:21:45.900 --> 00:21:46.900
And I think that that has been

00:21:46.900 --> 00:21:48.900
Some of the best that I've heard

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:52.900
That's very easy to not recognize

00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:53.900
At the beginning

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:55.900
Can you receive money?

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:56.900
Getting sponsors is great

00:21:56.900 --> 00:21:58.900
That helps with some of this

00:21:58.900 --> 00:21:59.900
But again, this is actually

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:00.900
Non-trivial sometimes

00:22:00.900 --> 00:22:02.900
How do actually people pay you?

00:22:02.900 --> 00:22:04.900
And then do people know

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:05.900
What they're paying for

00:22:05.900 --> 00:22:06.900
And how you'll use it?

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:08.900
I hear this a lot in open source

00:22:08.900 --> 00:22:09.900
I say it a lot myself

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:11.900
We're doing great work

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:13.900
Why don't they just give us money?

00:22:13.900 --> 00:22:16.900
That's not really how things work

00:22:16.900 --> 00:22:18.900
Unfortunately

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.900
But actually not unfortunately

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:22.900
People want to understand

00:22:22.900 --> 00:22:24.900
What they're paying for

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:25.900
And how you'll use it

00:22:25.900 --> 00:22:26.900
And so all of these other questions

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:29.900
About what's your governance structure?

00:22:29.900 --> 00:22:30.900
How do you make decisions?

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:32.900
All of these things is really important

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:34.900
Actually for getting money

00:22:34.900 --> 00:22:35.900
Because you can say

00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:40.900
We need money for one and a half developers

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:42.900
And someone to write documentation

00:22:42.900 --> 00:22:44.900
If we have this money

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:45.900
This person will do this

00:22:45.900 --> 00:22:47.900
This person will do this

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:49.900
You'll see at the end of the year

00:22:49.900 --> 00:22:52.900
That these features are implemented

00:22:52.900 --> 00:22:54.900
We have a maintenance structure

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:56.900
And we have a set of docs

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:58.900
That you and your team needs it

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:00.900
Again, there has to be

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:02.900
This kind of public good

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:05.900
Is really important and true

00:23:05.900 --> 00:23:08.900
But people need to understand

00:23:08.900 --> 00:23:09.900
How you're using money

00:23:09.900 --> 00:23:10.900
And have confidence

00:23:10.900 --> 00:23:12.900
That you actually know

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:14.900
How you're going to be spending money

00:23:17.900 --> 00:23:19.900
Okay, so Nadia Ekbal

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:21.900
As a part of this study

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:22.900
Interroads and Bridges

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:23.900
Also had this really nice

00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:25.900
This lemonade stand

00:23:25.900 --> 00:23:27.900
Handy guide to financial support for open source

00:23:27.900 --> 00:23:29.900
So it's a GitHub repository

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:30.900
If you Google it

00:23:30.900 --> 00:23:32.900
So she talks about a few different models

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:35.900
For open source structure

00:23:35.900 --> 00:23:37.900
And I do sort of

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:39.900
I'm not saying something's missing

00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:41.900
But that the piece of

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:42.900
Okay, this is how you bring the money in

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:44.900
But then how you spend it

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:45.900
And how you talk about how you spend it

00:23:45.900 --> 00:23:47.900
Is a complimentary piece

00:23:49.900 --> 00:23:51.900
So Posit

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:52.900
So one of the reasons

00:23:52.900 --> 00:23:54.900
I am super excited to be at Posit

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:57.900
And why I came to Posit in the first place

00:23:57.900 --> 00:23:59.900
Is because I think it's one of the

00:23:59.900 --> 00:24:02.900
A great model for supporting open source software

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:05.900
So we have this concept of a virtuous cycle

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:09.900
Where open source tools

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:10.900
Generate demand

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:12.900
They're great tools for data scientists

00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:13.900
They're free

00:24:13.900 --> 00:24:15.900
But then you need to transition often

00:24:15.900 --> 00:24:17.900
To like working in a corporate setting

00:24:17.900 --> 00:24:18.900
Where you have privacy

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.900
Or you need to work with teams

00:24:20.900 --> 00:24:22.900
And so then you need enterprise tools

00:24:22.900 --> 00:24:24.900
To enable you to use those open source tools

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.900
And so those are the products

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:28.900
That we build and sell

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:30.900
And then we use that to invest back

00:24:30.900 --> 00:24:31.900
In our pro products

00:24:31.900 --> 00:24:33.900
And our open source products

00:24:33.900 --> 00:24:35.900
And obviously this is hard

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:36.900
This is a big business

00:24:36.900 --> 00:24:38.900
Like there's 300 people

00:24:38.900 --> 00:24:40.900
JJ Leary's gonna talk next about Cordo

00:24:40.900 --> 00:24:42.900
And built this business

00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:43.900
Like this is non-trivial

00:24:43.900 --> 00:24:46.900
But I think it hits a lot of these marks

00:24:46.900 --> 00:24:48.900
Of like aligning your mission

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:50.900
With your ways of generating revenue

00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:52.900
Thinking about how you bring income

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:54.900
Thinking about governance structure

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:58.900
There's 43 people working full time

00:24:58.900 --> 00:25:00.900
On open source at Posit

00:25:00.900 --> 00:25:02.900
Even more working on other pieces

00:25:02.900 --> 00:25:04.900
Of open source within the company

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:06.900
But then even just within that

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:09.900
There are hundreds of open source products

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:11.900
And we actually don't necessarily

00:25:11.900 --> 00:25:12.900
Govern them all the same way

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:14.900
Because they have different goals

00:25:14.900 --> 00:25:16.900
So it's kind of a really interesting

00:25:16.900 --> 00:25:18.900
Ecosystem around a lot of these

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:20.900
Different pieces of we consider

00:25:20.900 --> 00:25:21.900
Maintenance

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:22.900
And I think one of the things

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:25.900
That's particularly great about it too

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:27.900
Is that because we have

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:29.900
So many open source developers

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:31.900
This idea of community of practice

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:33.900
So you in this room

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:34.900
Are not alone

00:25:34.900 --> 00:25:36.900
There is a community

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:37.900
That is working together

00:25:37.900 --> 00:25:38.900
In open source

00:25:38.900 --> 00:25:39.900
And Posit like

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:41.900
We get to experience it like

00:25:41.900 --> 00:25:42.900
Every day

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:43.900
Like that I get to see

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:44.900
My colleagues at this conference

00:25:44.900 --> 00:25:45.900
Is amazing

00:25:45.900 --> 00:25:47.900
Be on Slack with them

00:25:47.900 --> 00:25:48.900
It makes such a difference

00:25:48.900 --> 00:25:49.900
To have other people

00:25:49.900 --> 00:25:50.900
Working on open source

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:52.900
At the same time

00:25:52.900 --> 00:25:53.900
But there's a lot of other

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:54.900
Organizations out there

00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:56.900
That help create these structures

00:25:56.900 --> 00:25:58.900
The Kirk and Trudy's

00:25:58.900 --> 00:25:59.900
Are pretty assigned

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:00.900
These PyData meetings

00:26:00.900 --> 00:26:01.900
PyOpenSci

00:26:01.900 --> 00:26:02.900
PyLadies

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:03.900
RLadies

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:04.900
NumFocus

00:26:04.900 --> 00:26:05.900
And it's important

00:26:05.900 --> 00:26:06.900
To not go it alone

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:08.900
Because when you're feeling like

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:09.900
Maybe this is

00:26:09.900 --> 00:26:10.900
Like I'm not good at this

00:26:10.900 --> 00:26:12.900
It's actually usually not true

00:26:12.900 --> 00:26:14.900
It's just that it's hard

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:16.900
And so finding other people

00:26:16.900 --> 00:26:17.900
That you can share with

00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:18.900
Learn from

00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:19.900
Is really important

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:20.900
In this space

00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:24.900
So we in this room

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:26.900
Are building roads and bridges

00:26:26.900 --> 00:26:29.900
